Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back to GT's response with the bat. The official IPL pet, CHAMPAK, leads the way for the players as the Lucknow Super Giants' players spread out to the field. Now, the openers of the Gujarat Titans make their way out to the crease. Shubman Gill is joined by Sai Sudharsan, who comes in as the Impact Sub in place of Prasidh Krishna. There's a substitution in the Lucknow Super Giants' camp as well, as the centurion Mitchell Marsh has been subbed out, making way for Akash Singh, who will get the second innings underway with the ball. Off we go...
... THE RUN CHASE ...

With the playoffs looming, GT would be very disappointed with this ordinary bowling effort, knowing that such lapses could prove costly in high-stakes matches. It is now time for their batters, to complete this mountainous task up their sleeves. If the Super Giants manage to lay siege on the Titans' top order, they will be well ahead in the game. But can they get the better of any one of Shubman Gill or Sai Sudharsan early in the first six? A very exciting run chase is up next in just a few minutes.

Nicholas Pooran of Lucknow Super Giants is up for a quick chat with the broadcasters. He says that it is nice to contribute. Add that it has been difficult losing the last three games for them. Mentions that it was important to start well in the Powerplay and take responsibility, but you also have to respect the opposition. Says that the mid-season break did him good as he found his form again and says that it is good to see the fans out here supporting their teams and smiling after that unfortunate break. Tells that 235 is a good score, but it is also a good surface and hopes that the bowlers can execute their plans well and give them some happy moments.

The Bison powered his way to a well-earned century, smashing 100 off just 56 deliveries and cementing his place as the first overseas batter to achieve the feat this season. Meanwhile, Pooran wasted no time, blazing to his fifty in just 23 balls, piling on the misery for the Titans with his relentless hitting. As a result, the last 5 overs went for a whopping 75 runs, with only one over going under double digits in the second half of the first innings.

Rashid Khan endured another tough outing, struggling to contain the carnage as LSG’s batters ran riot. The rest of GT’s bowling attack looked out of sorts too, unable to put the brakes on the scoring or strike at crucial moments. Their premier wicket-taker, Prasidh Krishna, too, went for aplenty and wicketless, which sums up the day for them in the bowling. GT found themselves in deep waters, and with wickets in hand, Nicky P didn’t hold back, going all guns blazing to set up a high-voltage finish.

Despite Markram's departure after a 91-run opening stand, Marsh pushed the charge forward and notched yet another fifty. Nicholas Pooran too didn't flinch a bit to flex his muscles and played a good anchor. LSG controlled the middle phase as well, as runs kept leaking, with Marsh being the real aggressor.

The match started with a bang as both teams came out swinging, eager to take control right from the first ball. LSG’s openers, Markram and Marsh, didn’t waste any time settling in, making the most of their chances. including a couple of lucky escapes, to dominate the Powerplay, racking up 53 runs. With a solid start under their belt, the duo looked to shift gears, taking every opportunity to send the ball flying.

A bit of an anti-climactic end to the first half, with a dot ball, but a phenomenal batting display from the Lucknow Super Giants. 17 sixes were struck in the innings, the most by the Super Giants in a match so far in the IPL. Marsh turned his strong start into a blazing century, Pooran found his groove again after a mid-season slump, and Rishabh Pant delivered a clutch cameo. Talk about a dream performance! LSG must be kicking themselves, if only this kind of firepower had arrived a few matches earlier. At the pitch report, Simon Doull and Murali Kartik mentioned that 210 is the average first inning score at this venue, so, the Super Giants have gone well past that figure. Alarm bells in the GT camp?

PITCH REPORT - Simon Doull and Murali Kartik are inspecting the deck at the Narendra Modi Stadium. Doull first up says that it is a gorgeous evening and informs about the dimensions of the ground. Says it is 61 meters and 67 meters on the squares, while the straight hit is 70 meters. Points that this ground has been very consistent in terms of pace and bounce and has produced runs aplenty. Kartik joins him and observes that it is a green surface. Also says that pitch number 5 is being used for this game, while also highlighting that GT have won both their matches played here this season. Says the average first innings total is 210. Adds that teams have won batting first here. Further details that it is a black soil from Odisha and is pretty hard and rolled in nicely, with a fair sprinkling of grass. Reckons that seamers will get a good assistance, but also says it will be runs galore in Ahmedabad and feels batting first won't be a bad option here.

While we wait for the coin toss in Ahmedabad, let’s take a moment to glance over at Trent Bridge, where England and Zimbabwe are renewing their Test rivalry after more than two decades with a One-Off four-day Test. England, put to bat first, have wasted no time asserting themselves, launching their signature Bazball approach. Ben Duckett has already hammered a century in just 100 balls, while Zak Crawley is steadily closing in on his own milestone. Feel free to switch the tabs and tune in to soak up the action of Day 1 of that match.

The Super Giants have already beaten the Titans earlier this season when GT's batting lineup had one of those rare off days. Also, GT will be missing Jos Buttler during the playoffs as he heads off for England duty, so Kusal Mendis gets his shot to fill those big shoes. But that's for later. Tonight, LSG can pull off the double over the table-toppers, while GT, with a phenomenal home record of four wins out of five this year, aim to hit 20 points first this season and stay in the pole position. It is pride versus points at the lavish Narendra Modi Stadium! Stay tuned, toss and teams coming up shortly.

LSG's season feels like trying to solve a jigsaw puzzle with half the pieces missing. Mitchell Marsh and Aiden Markram have been doing the heavy lifting upfront, but the middle order has gone into hibernation mode when they need them most. Nicholas Pooran's bat has gone silent shockingly after a stellar first few matches, while Rishabh Pant just hasn’t found his rhythm this season. The bowling hasn't clicked either, with Ravi Bishnoi struggling to find his usual bite and Digvesh Singh picking the worst time to get suspended. While the pace attack lacks that important killer instinct.

Gujarat Titans are basically playing cricket on autopilot mode right now. Three wins straight, and now, home crowd behind them for their league’s last stretch, and every player stepping up when needed. Sai Sudharsan and Shubman Gill have both smashed past 600 runs this season, including that brutal 10-wicket demolition job last match against DC. Jos Buttler slotting in at three has been like adding extra armor to an already bulletproof lineup. Prasidh Krishna's having the season of his life with the ball, with the others chipping in with timely contributions, and here's the scary part – they're doing all this while Rashid Khan is still finding his groove.

Did someone fast-forward the IPL calendar? Usually, we're biting our nails till the final week, but this season's thrown us a curveball! Four teams have already booked their playoff spots with a week and many games to spare – Gujarat Titans, Royal Challengers Bengaluru, Punjab Kings, and Mumbai Indians are officially in the party! Now the real chess match begins as these qualified giants battle for those golden top-two positions that come with a safety net.

Hello, everyone! The Indian Premier League 2025 caravan rolls into the vibrant city of Ahmedabad, where tonight's clash pits table-toppers Gujarat Titans against the eliminated but not defeated Lucknow Super Giants in Match 64. GT wants to lock down that number one throne, while LSG? They're playing for nothing but pride and redemption on their minds.
... MATCH DAY ...

Match 64 of the 2025 Indian Premier League takes us to the Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad, where the Gujarat Titans host the Lucknow Super Giants. It will be a clash between two sides on divergent paths, with Gujarat eyeing a top-two finish while Lucknow, after their recent defeat, are officially out of playoff contention. The Titans currently sit comfortably atop the table with 18 points from 12 games. Two more wins would guarantee them a top-two spot, although even a single win could be enough if Punjab fail to win both of their remaining fixtures. GT’s success this season has been built around the brilliance of their top order, particularly the consistently outstanding Sai Sudharsan and Shubman Gill, with Jos Buttler chipping in as well. With the ball, Prasidh Krishna has been the spearhead, ably supported by Sai Kishore and Mohammed Siraj. What makes Gujarat's dominance even more impressive is that it has come despite Rashid Khan not hitting his usual heights and Kagiso Rabada being largely unavailable due to a provisional drug suspension. As for the Lucknow Super Giants, they are set to miss the playoffs for a second consecutive year. With pride on the line, they will now aim to disrupt GT’s top-two aspirations and those of RCB in their remaining fixtures. While Mitchell Marsh and Aiden Markram have offered solid starts, the middle order has failed to capitalise. Nicholas Pooran, after a bright start to the season, has faded, while captain and marquee signing Rishabh Pant has struggled to make any real impact. Lucknow’s bowling unit has lacked experience, and injuries have only compounded their problems. To make matters worse, they will be without Digvesh Singh for this match, who serves a one-game suspension following a third Code of Conduct breach. Still, the likes of Akash Deep, Will O'Rourke, and Avesh Khan will aim to test the in-form GT top order, while Ravi Bishnoi, despite a quiet season, remains a potential threat. Earlier in the season, LSG got the better of GT in Lucknow, but Ahmedabad has been a fortress for Gujarat, with the Titans winning their last four games at home. Can they make it five in a row and edge closer to a top-two finish? We shall find out.
